%I A394343 #73 Jun 14 2026 17:56:45
%S A394343 2,3,4,5,8,14,20,32,38,44,62,68,74,80,98,104,110,140,152,158,164,182,
%T A394343 200,212,224,230,242,272,278,284,308,314,332,338,350,368,374,380,398,
%U A394343 410,422,434,440,464,488,500,548,572,578,602,608,614,620,632,644,662,674,692,710,728
%N A394343 Numbers k >= 2 not expressible as (x*y + gcd(x-1,y-1) + 1)/2 with x, y >= 3.
%C A394343 Equivalently, with x /\ y = (x*y + gcd(x-1,y-1) + 1)/2 (the number of lattice points in a 60-degree corner triangle on the A2 lattice with legs of a and b points): x /\ y is commutative with identity 1, and 2 /\ z = z+1, so every k >= 3 has the trivial representation k = (k-1) /\ 2. The terms are the k with no representation using x, y >= 3.
%C A394343 Every term k > 5 satisfies k == 2 (mod 3).
%C A394343 Empirically every term k > 5 also satisfies k == 2 (mod 6) (checked to 10000).
%e A394343 4 is a term: its only representation 4 = x /\ y uses a leg of 2 (4 = 3 /\ 2), and there is no x, y >= 3 with (x*y + gcd(x-1,y-1) + 1)/2 = 4.
%e A394343 7 is not a term: 7 = 4 /\ 3 since (4*3 + gcd(3,2) + 1)/2 = (12 + 1 + 1)/2 = 7, a nontrivial representation.
%e A394343 10 is not a term: 10 = 4 /\ 4 since (16 + gcd(3,3) + 1)/2 = (16 + 3 + 1)/2 = 10 (also 10 = 6 /\ 3).
%e A394343 8 is a term: representations of 8 are only 8 = 7 /\ 2; no x, y >= 3 work.
%o A394343 (PARI)
%o A394343 istp(n) = { my(t = 2*n - 1); for(a = 3, n-1, for(b = 3, a, if(a*b + gcd(a-1,b-1) == t, return(0)); if(a*b > t + a, break))); 1; }
%o A394343 select(istp, [2..1000])
%Y A394343 Cf. A000217, A000326, A016933, A049727.
%K A394343 nonn,easy
%O A394343 1,1
